{{other people||Gareth Jones (disambiguation)}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}
{{Use British English|date=September 2012}}
'''Gareth Jones''' (6 June 1925 &ndash; 30 November 1958) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] actor, born in [[Lampeter]], [[Wales]], chiefly remembered for the circumstances of his death.

During a [[live television]] broadcast of the ''[[Armchair Theatre]]'' play ''[[Underground (1958 TV play)|Underground]]'' on the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] network in the UK on 30 November 1958, Jones suffered a massive heart attack and died while off-camera between two of his scenes. Some contemporary news reports stated that he had suffered the heart attack while on camera,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=AItfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jOoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4202,188958&dq=gareth+jones&hl=en|title=The Miami News - Google News Archive Search|work=google.com}}</ref> although most references claim that he was stricken while in a make-up chair, between scenes. However, actor [[Peter Bowles]], also in the cast, recalled that "During transmission, a little group of us was talking on camera while awaiting the arrival of Gareth Jones's character, who had some information for us. We could see him coming up towards us, but we saw him fall. We had no idea what had happened, but he certainly wasn't coming our way".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2009/may/31/television-drama-theatre|title=Live TV drama is resurrected as Sky shrugs off lessons of history|author=Gareth Rubin|work=the Guardian}}</ref>

Director [[Ted Kotcheff]] and the remaining cast were forced to improvise to carry the play to its conclusion, with producer [[Sydney Newman]] ordering Kotcheff to "shoot it like a football match". Coincidentally, Jones's character was to have suffered a heart attack during the play.

Jones had appeared in three other ''[[Armchair Theatre]]'' plays in 1958 - "Noon On Doomsday" (6 July 1958),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1098450/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_1|title=Armchair Theatre - Noon on Doomsday (TV Episode 1958)|work=IMDb}}</ref> "Trial By Candlelight" (22 June 1958),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0793673/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_1|title=Armchair Theatre - Trial by Candlelight (TV Episode 1958)|work=IMDb}}</ref> and "Miss Olive" (6 April 1958).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1098446/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_1|title=Armchair Theatre Miss Olive (TV Episode 1958)|work=IMDb}}</ref> Other TV appearances included the ITV Television Playhouse production of "Thunder On Sycamore Street" (11 October 1957),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0908911/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_3|title=ITV Television Playhouse - Thunder on Sycamore Street (TV Episode 1957)|work=IMDb}}</ref>  the [[BBC Television]] adaptation of ''[[Under Milk Wood]]'' (9 May 1957),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0409416/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_5|title=Under Milk Wood (TV Movie 1957)|date=9 May 1957|work=IMDb}}</ref> the BBC series "Onion Boys" (1957),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1632949/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_2|title=Onion Boys (TV Series 1957–1958)|work=IMDb}}</ref> and "A Tale Of Two Cities" (1957).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0423750/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_4|title=A Tale of Two Cities (TV Mini-Series 1957)|work=IMDb}}</ref>

He earlier appeared in [[Dundee Repertory Theatre]] plays including "Petticoat Influence" (1952),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://special.lib.gla.ac.uk/sta/search/detaile.cfm?EID=14833|title=Scottish Theatre Archive - Event Details|website=special.lib.gla.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref><ref>Dundee Courier, 29 July 1952</ref> ''[[The Beaver Coat]]'' (1952),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://special.lib.gla.ac.uk/sta/search/detaile.cfm?EID=14844|title=Scottish Theatre Archive - Event Details|website=special.lib.gla.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref><ref>Dundee Courier, 12 August 1952</ref> "The Hollow Crown" (1952),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://special.lib.gla.ac.uk/sta/search/detaile.cfm?EID=14848|title=Scottish Theatre Archive - Event Details|website=special.lib.gla.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref><ref>Dundee Courier, 26 August 1952</ref> "The Queen's Husband" (1952),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://special.lib.gla.ac.uk/sta/search/detaile.cfm?EID=14852|title=Scottish Theatre Archive - Event Details|website=special.lib.gla.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref><ref>Dundee Courier, 9 September 1952</ref> "Young Madame Conti" (1952),<ref>Dundee Courier, 23 September 1952</ref> and ''[[The Lark (play)|The Lark]]'' (1955).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://special.lib.gla.ac.uk/sta/search/detaile.cfm?EID=26046|title=Scottish Theatre Archive - Event Details|website=special.lib.gla.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref>

